      <title>Re: any official word on spell dmg vs. melee dmg?</title>
      <link>http://eqforums.station.sony.com/eq/board/message?board.id=Progression&amp;message.id=6505#M6505</link>
      <description>&lt;div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;span&gt;&lt;br&gt;&lt;blockquote&gt;&lt;hr&gt;Burncrew187 wrote:&lt;br&gt;I wont get too far into opinion, alot of people share the same opinion as me on the previous caster vs melee posts, but some don't.  I'll just stick to the facts.&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;In 2005, druid, wizard, magician, cleric, shaman, necromancer, wizard, and enchanter spells were upgraded to more damage, and/or be more mana efficient. Spells 1-50 did less damage and costed more mana before 2005. They did this to make casters as par with the expansions released up to dragons of norrath.&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;The thought, and truth behind this was that ever since kunark, melee weapons 1-50 have been upgraded various times, however caster spells always stayed the same. They always did the same damage, and costed the same mana. In 2005, as I stated before, they upgraded spells to do considerably more amounts of damage.&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;This was a great update, everyone I knew including myself loved it. It made alot of sense, probably one of the few great things SoE did for free, however since the topic of a progression server comes up, the spells that were upgraded in 2005, to balence and trivialize casters with melees, are now global across all servers, which holds true in the fact that they'll be held on the new progression server.&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;What's the problem with this? It's that melees are going to be using old world weapons, and casters are going to be using new world upgraded spells that were meant to put casters at par with the 2005 state of everquest.&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;It's like putting modern engine parts in an old car frame. Casters are going to be on overdrive for a long time with their upgraded spells, untill expansions are released to put melee's back at part with casters.&lt;br&gt;&lt;div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;br&gt;&lt;hr&gt;&lt;/blockquote&gt;&lt;br&gt;Yeah, some spells do more damage now... I think keeping the current newbie quest rewards in is a mistake though.  Anything which increases the damage a party or raid can do over what was available against content in the old world is a negative in my opinion, and should be altered if reasonably possible.  That is, I think some line has to be drawn on what work is reasonable to invest on such issues... and then anything which doesn't cross that line should be worked on.  With spells being a global phenomena (and the initial DEV response) it sounds as though reverting them surpasses that line.&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;Much of the current newbie quest gear (not the original newbie quest gear, mind you - the current, upgraded stuff) is better than anything you'll see in the old world for the first 40 levels or so.   Including it obsoletes 80% (4/5, a ball-park figure) of that content available to players.  Further, it creates camping issues on the part of higher level players in newbie zones for newbie quest completion.  Assuming quest rewards aren't global (and from DEV responses, it sounds as if they're not) it would be wise to change or disable these).&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;Any increase in gear power to equalize melees and casters would be unwise.  It will directly result in people levelling faster than they should, mobs falling faster than they should, and expansions being unlocked faster than they should.&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;Contrary to what has been advertised, the revised spells will not obsolete melees.  Warriors, Paladins and Shadowknights will still be needed to hold aggro (and, indeed, with cloth casters falling as fast as ever, increased spell damage will make aggro management even more key to a successful group), monks will still be needed to flop on pulls, rangers will also benefit DPS-wise from revised spells...&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;...the only class that will really be hit significantly by this is the rogue class, and if the decision comes down to having a gimpy rogue class until kunark is unlocked or introducing gear for all classes which trivializes such a large percentage of old world content by L12... well, I'd feel sorry for the rogues.&lt;br&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;</description>
