      <title>Re: any official word on spell dmg vs. melee dmg?</title>
      <link>http://eqforums.station.sony.com/eq/board/message?board.id=Progression&amp;message.id=6530#M6530</link>
      <description>&lt;div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;br&gt;&lt;blockquote&gt;&lt;hr&gt;JakeTheBarbarian wrote:&lt;p&gt;i played a mage and it did seem fairly powerful compared to the mobs for those early levels.  the pet alone could solo a lot of things, and the nukes were doing some major damage.  I made level ten in a few hours.  could that be considered overpowered?  it seemed a little too easy to me, so I'd say for the content they are somewhat.  I hope 10 through 20 are a little more of a struggle. &lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;I haven't tried a mellee for comparison.  I'd be interested what other people who have tried one from nothing experienced. &lt;br&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;hr&gt;&lt;/blockquote&gt;&lt;p&gt;Not all that surprising really, especially using a Magician.  Casters in general have an advantage starting out with nothing because they are less gear dependant than melees early on.  Look at your Magician example.  Whereas a melee character would need as much armor and the best weapon he/she can buy at levels 1 - 10 in order to solo mobs, you just need your earth pet, some malachite, and your best nuke spell and you're set to go.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;With time, though, the curve will level out as everyone needs to upgrade gear in order to keep being effective.  Like I said, I'm hardly worried about casters having an early advantage with spells.  They might get groups a little more often, but most groups I've been in aren't too picky about whatever DPS they can get, especially when they need it right away (as has been the case in most pick up groups I've been in).  Most groups aren't going to go without a tank that can hold agro, a caster is no good if he/she is getting pummled to death.  If anything, I expect the &amp;quot;holy trinity&amp;quot; (Tank/Cleric/Enchanter) to be alive and well for the first few months as it was when this game first went live.  You might see a &amp;quot;creative&amp;quot; group of 6 casters try the ole Stun &amp;amp; AoE as many mobs as possible all at once, but I don't think they'll get away with that long given the competitiveness the old world dungeons will see.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;As for soloers, who cares?  Casters have always had an easier time soloing by virtue of being able to avoid meleeing the mob while they nuke/DoT them from a distance, having their pets tank for them while they nuke/DoT the mob, or snaring the mob, fearing it, and loading DoT after DoT on it.  Hell, Druids and Wizards have been infamous in the past for snaring 4 mobs at once and doing the dreaded &amp;quot;quad kite&amp;quot; using certain AoE DD spells on them.  None of this will really stop short of a major nerf to their spells, and it's hardly a concern now.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;Anyways, I don't see much reason to freak out about it.  I think most people are going to end up playing whatever class they find interesting.  If they get some short lived perks because of it, so be it.&lt;br&gt;&lt;/p&gt;</description>
